      "type": "Term",
      "front": "Church and School",
      "back": "Many moved to southern towns and cities, where, it seemed, \"freedom was free-er.\" With slavery dead, institutions that had existed before the war, like the black family, free blacks' churches and schools, and the secret slave church, were strengthened, expanded, and freed from white supervision. Houston, pastor of the city's Third African Baptist Church, and James Porter, an Episcopal religious leader who had operated a secret school for black children before the war, in a few years would win election to the Georgia legislature. Briefly explain the ways in which black families, churches, schools, and other institutions contributed to the development of African-American culture and political activism in period 1865 to 1877.",
