      "chapterId": "chapter15",
      "type": "Person",
      "front": "Thaddeus Stevens",
      "back": "Radical Republican leader. The most prominent Radicals in Congress were Charles Sumner, a senator from Massachusetts, and Thaddeus Stevens, a lawyer and iron manufacturer who represented Pennsylvania in the House of Representatives. \"The same national authority,\" declared Sumner, \"that destroyed slavery must see that this other pretension [racial inequality] is not permitted to survive.\" Thaddeus Stevens's most cherished aim was to confiscate the land of disloyal planters and divide it among former slaves and northern migrants to the South. Thaddeus Stevens appears throughout \"What Is Freedom?\": Reconstruction as a major historical actor.",
