      "chapterId": "chapter15",
      "type": "Person",
      "front": "Frederick Douglass",
      "back": "Advocate for black citizenship and rights. As Frederick Douglass put it soon after the South's surrender in 1865, \"Slavery is not abolished until the black man has the ballot.\" In a \"monarchial government,\" Douglass explained, no \"special\" disgrace applied to those denied the right to vote. Frederick Douglass appears throughout \"What Is Freedom?\": Reconstruction as a major historical actor.",
